{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775848257527,"sessionID":"ses_287331ec5ffe8Mnu800CZapmVx","part":{"id":"prt_d78cd7a71001uk0KvsB0wnO0r9","messageID":"msg_d78cd57ff001cbW8Vix1deD9TM","sessionID":"ses_287331ec5ffe8Mnu800CZapmVx","type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_d70ad780edd345b9af715a8f","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"content":"# Proposal: AR-010 — Router 会话管理\n\n## Summary\n\nImplement session management capabilities in `pkg/router` to track, manage, and persist user sessions when routing to AgentRuntime and CodeInterpreter backends. This enables sticky sessions, session affinity, session lifecycle management, and provides operational visibility into active sessions.\n\n## Purpose\n\n### Background\n\nThe AR-009 router implements HTTP reverse proxying to dynamically route requests to AgentRuntime and CodeInterpreter sandboxes. Currently:\n\n- **No session tracking**: Requests are routed without awareness of session context\n- **No sticky sessions**: Load balancing distributes requests across backends without session affinity\n- **No session lifecycle**: No mechanism to track when sessions start/end\n- **No session state visibility**: No way to query active sessions or session metadata\n\n### Goal\n\nProvide session management that:\n- Tracks active sessions with unique identifiers\n- Supports sticky sessions (session affinity based on session ID)\n- Manages session lifecycle (creation, expiration, cleanup)\n- Provides session metadata storage (user ID, backend, start time, last activity)\n- Enables session-based access control\n- Exports session metrics for monitoring\n\n### Value\n- Enables consistent user experience with sticky sessions\n- Provides audit trail for session activity\n- Supports session-based rate limiting per user\n- Enables session expiration for resource management\n- Improves operational visibility\n\n---\n\n## Scope\n\n### In-Scope\n\n| Deliverable | Description |\n|-------------|-------------|\n| Session Store | In-memory store for session tracking with thread-safe operations |\n| Session ID Generation | Generate unique session IDs (UUID or similar) |\n| Session Affinity | Route requests to the same backend based on session cookie/header |\n| Session Lifecycle | Create, update, expire, and delete sessions |\n| Session Middleware | HTTP middleware to extract/inject session ID |\n| Session Metrics | Track active sessions, session rates, expirations |\n| Session Configuration | Configurable session timeout, cookie name, storage options |\n| Unit Tests | Core session logic coverage >70% |\n\n### Code Structure\n\n```\npkg/router/\n├── session/\n│   ├── session.go           # Session struct and interface\n│   ├── store.go             # Session store implementation\n│   ├── manager.go           # Session lifecycle manager\n│   └── config.go            # Session configuration\n├── middleware/\n│   └── session.go           # Session middleware for HTTP\n└── (existing files...)\n```\n\n### Configuration\n\nThe router supports these new session configuration options:\n\n| Option | Type | Default | Description |\n|--------|------|---------|-------------|\n| SessionEnabled | bool | false | Enable session management |\n| SessionTimeout | duration | 30m | Session expiration time |\n| SessionCookieName | string | \"AGENTSESSIONID\" | Cookie/header name for session ID |\n| SessionCookieDomain | string | \"\" | Cookie domain (empty = current domain) |\n| SessionCookieSecure | bool | true | Set Secure flag on cookie |\n| SessionCookieHTTPOnly | bool | true | Set HttpOnly flag on cookie |\n| SessionMaxActive | int | 10000 | Max concurrent sessions |\n| SessionCleanupInterval | duration | 5m | Interval for expired session cleanup |\n\n### Out-of-Scope\n- Distributed session store (Redis, etcd) — future enhancement\n- Session persistence to Kubernetes CRD — future enhancement\n- Session replication across router instances\n- OIDC/OAuth2 session integration (use existing auth middleware)\n\n---\n\n## Impact Analysis\n\n### Dependencies\n\n| Dependency | Source | Purpose |\n|------------|--------|---------|\n| github.com/google/uuid | ^1.6 | Session ID generation |\n| github.com/volcano/sh/agentcube/pkg/apis/runtime/v1alpha1 | local | CR types for session correlation |\n| github.com/volcano/sh/agentcube/pkg/router | local | Existing router module |\n\n### Upstream Dependencies\n\n- **AR-009 Router Core** — Provides the reverse proxy foundation\n- **AR-007 K8s Reconciler** — Creates backends that sessions connect to\n\n### Downstream Consumers\n\n1. **External Clients** — Benefit from sticky sessions and consistent experience\n2. **Monitoring Systems** — Session metrics for operational visibility\n3. **Auth System** — Session-based access control integration\n\n### Risks\n\n| Risk | Severity | Mitigation |\n|------|----------|------------|\n| Memory exhaustion | Medium | Max session limit, automatic cleanup |\n| Session hijacking | Medium | Secure cookies, server-side session storage |\n| Session race conditions | Low | Thread-safe store implementation |\n| Cookie manipulation | Medium | Validate session ID format, server-side lookup |\n\n---\n\n## Alternatives Considered\n\n### Option 1: Cookie-Based Session with Backend Affinity (Selected)\n\n**Approach**: Use HTTP cookies to track session ID, route to the same backend based on session mapping.\n\n**Pros**:\n- Simple client integration (browser handles cookies)\n- Works with existing routing layer\n- Low overhead for session tracking\n\n**Cons**:\n- Requires cookie support in client\n- Sticky sessions may cause uneven load\n\n**Decision**: Selected — provides the best balance of simplicity and functionality.\n\n---\n\n### Option 2: JWT-Based Session Management\n\n**Approach**: Use JWT tokens containing session claims, validate at router level.\n\n**Pros**:\n- Stateless, no server-side storage needed\n- Built-in expiration\n- Cryptographically verified\n\n**Cons**:\n- Cannot revoke active sessions\n- Larger token size\n- More complex implementation\n\n**Decision**: Rejected — stateless nature prevents session management features like forced logout.\n\n---\n\n### Option 3: External Session Store (Redis)\n\n**Approach**: Store sessions in Redis for distributed access.\n\n**Pros**:\n- Shared state across router instances\n- Persistence beyond process lifetime\n\n**Cons**:\n- Adds external dependency\n- Network latency for session operations\n- Additional infrastructure requirement\n\n**Decision**: Rejected — adds complexity; in-memory store suffices for single-instance deployment.\n\n---\n\n### Option 4: Client-Side Session (URL Rewriting)\n\n**Approach**: Encode session ID in URL paths.\n\n**Pros**:\n- Works without cookies\n\n**Cons**:\n- URL pollution\n- Security concerns\n- Not suitable for REST APIs\n\n**Decision**: Rejected — not appropriate for API-focused routing.\n\n---\n\n## Implementation Plan\n\n### Phase 1: Session Core\n- [ ] Define Session struct with ID, UserID, Backend, StartTime, LastActivity, Metadata\n- [ ] Implement SessionStore interface with thread-safe operations\n- [ ] Implement in-memory SessionStore with map and RWMutex\n- [ ] Add session ID generation (UUID v4)\n\n### Phase 2: Session Middleware\n- [ ] Extract session ID from cookie or X-Session-ID header\n- [ ] Create new session if not exists (when SessionEnabled)\n- [ ] Inject session cookie in response\n- [ ] Update last activity on each request\n\n### Phase 3: Session Affinity\n- [ ] Modify RouteHandler to check session affinity\n- [ ] Store backend key in session\n- [ ] Route to stored backend when session exists\n- [ ] Handle backend removal with session invalidation\n\n### Phase 4: Session Lifecycle\n- [ ] Implement session expiration checking\n- [ ] Add background goroutine for cleanup\n- [ ] Handle session deletion on backend removal\n- [ ] Add configuration for timeout and limits\n\n### Phase 5: Metrics and Observability\n- [ ] Add session counter (active, created, expired)\n- [ ] Add session rate metrics\n- [ ] Add session duration histogram\n- [ ] Export session metrics to Prometheus\n\n### Phase 6: Testing\n- [ ] Unit tests for SessionStore operations\n- [ ] Unit tests for session middleware\n- [ ] Unit tests for session affinity\n- [ ] Mock tests for session lifecycle\n\n---\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Session store supports create, get, update, delete operations\n- [ ] Session ID is generated as UUID v4\n- [ ] Session cookie is set on first request when enabled\n- [ ] Subsequent requests with same cookie route to same backend\n- [ ] Sessions expire after configured timeout\n- [ ] Expired sessions are cleaned up automatically\n- [ ] Session metrics are exported (active_sessions, session_created_total, session_expired_total)\n- [ ] Max session limit is enforced\n- [ ] Session data includes user ID, backend, start time, last activity\n- [ ] Unit tests pass with >70% coverage\n- [ ] Graceful shutdown closes session store","filePath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-MiniMax-M2.5_20260410T163134Z/proposal.md"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.\n\nLSP errors detected in other files:\n<diagnostics file=\"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-MiniMax-M2.5_20260410T163134Z/pkg/client/informers/externalversions/runtime/v1alpha1/interface.go\">\nERROR [4:2] \"github.com/volcano-sh/agentcube/pkg/apis/runtime/v1alpha1\" imported and not used\n</diagnostics>\n\nLSP errors detected in other files:\n<diagnostics file=\"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-MiniMax-M2.5_20260410T163134Z/pkg/workloadmanager/server_test.go\">\nERROR [15:2] \"k8s.io/apimachinery/pkg/watch\" imported and not used\nERROR [66:14] cannot use &metav1.Status{…} (value of type *\"k8s.io/apimachinery/pkg/apis/meta/v1\".Status) as error value in return statement: *\"k8s.io/apimachinery/pkg/apis/meta/v1\".Status does not implement error (missing method Error)\nERROR [81:9] cannot use &metav1.St